01:28:24.240 --> 01:28:26.960
We can have it annulled
in the morning.

01:28:27.120 --> 01:28:30.540
Oh, you did?
Good.

01:28:30.710 --> 01:28:35.050
Well, a 12-hour marriage.
Even shorter than my first one.

01:28:36.340 --> 01:28:38.010
Peterson,
you were married before?

01:28:38.180 --> 01:28:40.430
You find that so hard
to imagine?

01:28:40.590 --> 01:28:45.470
No, no. I'm just sort of particular
about who my wives have been married to.

01:28:45.640 --> 01:28:48.980
- Who was he?
- Name's O'Connor.

01:28:49.140 --> 01:28:52.690
Of Peterson, Peterson
and O'Connor.

01:28:52.860 --> 01:28:55.820
He's extremely close
with my parents.

01:28:55.980 --> 01:28:59.530
- Well, you've been married before, right?
- I tried it briefly.

01:28:59.700 --> 01:29:00.820
Didn't like it?

01:29:00.990 --> 01:29:03.160
No, actually it was my wife
who had the complaint.

01:29:03.330 --> 01:29:07.120
She said I was never home. She said
I loved newspapering more than her...

01:29:07.290 --> 01:29:11.000
She said she'd never mean as much to
you as the story you were working on.

01:29:11.170 --> 01:29:14.000
- She said she was jealous of the boys...
- In the City room.

01:29:14.170 --> 01:29:15.300
- Yeah!
- Funny.

01:29:15.460 --> 01:29:16.460
Yeah.

01:29:17.590 --> 01:29:21.050
She's now married to a brilliant
CPA with an amazing sweater collection.

01:29:21.220 --> 01:29:24.010
- Bet he's home every night.
- Like clockwork.

01:29:24.180 --> 01:29:26.520
- That's what they like.
- Regularity.

01:29:26.680 --> 01:29:27.680
Yeah.

01:29:35.150 --> 01:29:37.690
You know, Brackett...

01:29:37.860 --> 01:29:40.260
some guys...

01:29:41.860 --> 01:29:45.870
might try to take advantage of
a situation like this, but not you.

01:29:46.030 --> 01:29:47.430
No, no.

01:29:48.160 --> 01:29:51.500
I know this is the one area...

01:29:51.670 --> 01:29:54.540
- where I can completely trust you.
- Mm-hmm.

01:29:57.050 --> 01:29:58.880
So, which side of the heart
do you want?

01:29:59.050 --> 01:30:02.050
- We're sleeping in shifts. Remember?
- Yeah, right. I forgot.

01:30:02.220 --> 01:30:05.260
- Um, you want to take the first shift?
- No, no, you go ahead.

01:30:05.430 --> 01:30:06.430
Mmm.

01:30:28.370 --> 01:30:31.620
Tell me something, Brackett.

01:30:33.870 --> 01:30:36.710
What is it about me
you don't like?

01:30:36.880 --> 01:30:38.920
I'm not pretty enough?

01:30:39.090 --> 01:30:41.970
Not tall enough?
Too tall?

01:30:42.130 --> 01:30:45.930
Too smart?
Not smart enough?

01:30:46.090 --> 01:30:49.100
Wrong color hair?

01:30:49.260 --> 01:30:51.730
Talk too much?

01:30:51.890 --> 01:30:54.270
Really, what is it?

01:30:54.440 --> 01:30:58.610
I've never had this effect
on a man before.

01:30:58.770 --> 01:31:00.860
You would be surprised, but...

01:31:01.030 --> 01:31:06.320
most men are actually
somewhat attracted to me.

01:31:06.490 --> 01:31:10.790
I know you think I'm trouble,
and you curse the day you met me...

01:31:10.950 --> 01:31:15.000
but off the record, I don't feel
that way about you...

01:31:15.170 --> 01:31:16.570
at all.

01:31:23.970 --> 01:31:27.050
Off the record, Peterson...

01:31:27.220 --> 01:31:29.890
I don't feel that way
about you, either...

01:31:30.060 --> 01:31:31.460
at all.

01:31:34.060 --> 01:31:36.060
You don't?

01:31:50.450 --> 01:31:53.200
First time I ever kissed
a newspaperman.

01:31:53.370 --> 01:31:55.370
I like it.

01:31:57.870 --> 01:32:03.460
This doesn't change anything.
I'm still the Globe, and you're still...

01:32:03.630 --> 01:32:07.340
The Chronicle.
I know, Sabrina, I know.

01:32:07.510 --> 01:32:11.260
- We're still...
- Competitors.

01:32:12.640 --> 01:32:15.640
Thank you
for calling me Sabrina.

01:32:27.360 --> 01:32:30.200
- Hello?
- This is Mrs. Hervey.

01:32:30.370 --> 01:32:33.580
If you want to see my husband,
please come now.

01:32:33.740 --> 01:32:37.750
This is exactly the sort of thing that
would've driven my ex-husband crazy.

01:32:37.910 --> 01:32:41.670
Your current husband's not
too thrilled about it, either.

01:32:44.340 --> 01:32:45.800
- Well...
- Yeah.

01:32:45.960 --> 01:32:46.960
Yeah.

01:32:50.840 --> 01:32:53.510
Oh, hey, don't forget
your wallet.

01:33:09.990 --> 01:33:11.790
Shall we?

01:33:14.580 --> 01:33:15.580
Sure.

01:33:17.500 --> 01:33:19.660
My husband's home now
because there's nothing more

01:33:19.830 --> 01:33:22.460
they can do for him at the hospital.

01:33:22.630 --> 01:33:26.050
But some days
he's not all that bad.

01:33:26.210 --> 01:33:31.220
Alex, the reporters from Chicago
are here to see you.

01:33:33.510 --> 01:33:34.510
Alex?

01:33:40.730 --> 01:33:41.730
Alex.

01:33:43.610 --> 01:33:47.820
Alex, they've come
such a long way to see you.

01:33:49.990 --> 01:33:54.240
You wanted to talk to my husband
about, um, Darryl Beekman, didn't you?

01:33:54.410 --> 01:33:58.250
Mm-hmm. Yes, we were wondering
why, a-after the success of LDF...

01:33:58.410 --> 01:34:01.000
that your husband
was given a promotion...

01:34:01.160 --> 01:34:03.290
but Dr. Beekman chose
to leave the company?

01:34:03.460 --> 01:34:08.460
Were you wondering, Mr. Brackett,
or do you think you know?

01:34:08.630 --> 01:34:11.420
We think we know. We just need
someone to tell us if we're right.

01:34:11.590 --> 01:34:14.510
Did your husband ever say
anything about Dr. Beekman...

01:34:14.680 --> 01:34:16.180
about disagreements
between them?

01:34:16.350 --> 01:34:17.550
Never.

01:34:18.310 --> 01:34:22.310
I... I'm sorry. I w... I was hoping
Alex could talk to you.

01:34:22.480 --> 01:34:25.270
I sensed that he wanted to.

01:34:27.940 --> 01:34:32.200
Uh, uh, excuse me. Can I use
your restroom for a second?

01:34:32.360 --> 01:34:34.990
- Down the hall.
- Oh, thank you.

01:34:36.280 --> 01:34:38.990
I'm sorry you had to come
such a long way.

01:34:39.160 --> 01:34:43.420
I really appreciate you calling
us, Mrs. Hervey. Thank you.

01:34:46.960 --> 01:34:49.670
Maybe we should wait
until Mr. Brackett gets back.

01:34:49.840 --> 01:34:51.420
No, no, that's okay.

01:34:51.590 --> 01:34:53.800
Uh, I really don't know
what it is, but...

01:34:53.970 --> 01:34:57.350
I thought it was strange,
because in 30 years...

01:34:57.510 --> 01:35:01.470
I've never seen Alex bring
anything home from work.

01:35:03.520 --> 01:35:09.020
You can take it, but I'm afraid it's
not much use to anyone outside of Chess.

01:35:10.400 --> 01:35:12.400
Thank you.

01:35:40.060 --> 01:35:42.560
This is Captain Riley. Just to let
you know that we're ahead of schedule...

01:35:42.720 --> 01:35:46.310
and we'll be arriving in Chicago
in just a little under an hour.

01:35:46.480 --> 01:35:50.730
The temperature is e breezy
34 degrees with clear skies.

01:35:56.490 --> 01:35:59.280
- Sorry.
- No problem.

01:35:59.450 --> 01:36:02.540
Complimentary champagne
for the bride and groom?

01:36:02.700 --> 01:36:05.410
I can always spot the newlyweds
on our Vegas flights.

01:36:05.580 --> 01:36:07.920
Of course with you two,
who couldn't?

01:36:11.540 --> 01:36:14.380
- Congratulations.
- Thank you.

01:36:17.630 --> 01:36:19.390
So, what should we drink to?

01:36:21.930 --> 01:36:24.640
- Our annulment?
- Perfect!

01:36:24.810 --> 01:36:28.190
Because, truthfully, Brackett, there's not a
man in the world I'd rather annul than you.

01:36:29.940 --> 01:36:32.940
Truthfully, Peterson, I wouldn't
believe anything you ever said...

01:36:33.110 --> 01:36:35.860
that started with
the word "truthfully."

01:36:46.000 --> 01:36:48.580
Well, I guess it's time
to put an end to the Charade.

01:36:48.750 --> 01:36:52.920
Yeah. Gimbel's marries Macy's.
We wouldn't want that to get around.

01:37:05.520 --> 01:37:07.930
- May I?
- Mmm.

01:37:18.860 --> 01:37:23.280
Will you do something for me,
Peterson, for old times' sake?

01:37:25.490 --> 01:37:26.490
What?

01:37:30.620 --> 01:37:33.040
Kiss me good-bye.

01:38:19.510 --> 01:38:23.380
Back now, 7:30 on this, uh,
Monday morning, October the 14th.

01:38:23.550 --> 01:38:26.600
I'm Bryant Gumbel here in Studio 3B.
Katie Couric's up on Capitol...

01:38:26.760 --> 01:38:29.310
What happened to October 13th?

01:38:40.900 --> 01:38:42.530
Let's go.

01:38:49.580 --> 01:38:52.960
Uh, I'm here
for the 4:00 tour.

01:38:53.120 --> 01:38:55.630
In beautiful
Spring Creek, Wisconsin.

01:38:55.790 --> 01:38:57.750
Our first stop
on today's tour...

01:38:57.920 --> 01:39:01.130
is going to be the Chess Family
Science Discovery Center.

01:39:01.300 --> 01:39:05.840
Now, as we walk in pairs down
the Biology of Tomorrow corridor...

01:39:06.010 --> 01:39:08.850
Right this way, sir.
How are you folks today?

01:39:09.010 --> 01:39:14.350
I'd like to point out a few of the
everyday products created here at Chess.

01:39:14.520 --> 01:39:17.900
For example, the cold medicine
which I forgot to take this morning.

01:39:23.860 --> 01:39:27.490
- Hi.
- Milk, e staple for the entire family.

01:39:27.660 --> 01:39:31.450
And just one of the products
Chess Chemical is working to improve...

01:39:31.620 --> 01:39:33.160
- for the 21st century.
- You know, you look very familiar.

01:39:33.330 --> 01:39:34.370
Have we met before?

01:39:34.540 --> 01:39:38.290
No. Actually this is my first
visit to the Twilight Zone.

01:39:38.460 --> 01:39:41.960
- Why'd you double-cross me, Peterson?
- Just following the Golden Rule.

01:39:42.130 --> 01:39:44.630
But I thought we were partners,
five-oh, five-oh.

01:39:44.800 --> 01:39:47.550
That must explain why you took
Kim's security pass.

01:39:47.720 --> 01:39:49.300
- Oh, Peterson, I was gonna...
- "l was gonna tell you."

01:39:49.470 --> 01:39:51.600
You can't even be honest
about being dishonest.

01:39:51.760 --> 01:39:54.520
I was gonna tell you, Peterson.
I took it as a backup.

01:39:54.680 --> 01:39:57.810
- I never thought we'd be here again.
- Yeah, mm-hmm.

01:39:57.980 --> 01:40:00.570
- Look, I gotta go.
- Peterson, listen.

01:40:00.730 --> 01:40:02.650
It's not safe for you
to be here alone.

01:40:02.820 --> 01:40:05.030
Now, you probably don't wanna be
reminded of this...

01:40:05.190 --> 01:40:08.570
but I did take an oath to protect you
'til death do us part.

01:40:08.740 --> 01:40:10.490
Game's over, Brackett,
and you lose.

01:40:10.660 --> 01:40:12.580
I've got the disk.
I've got the security pass.

01:40:12.740 --> 01:40:14.910
Actually, I have the disk.

01:40:15.080 --> 01:40:17.460
Actually, that's blank.

01:40:17.620 --> 01:40:19.880
I've got the disk.
I've got my own security pass.

01:40:20.040 --> 01:40:22.340
And I've got the authority
to have you thrown out of here.

01:40:22.500 --> 01:40:25.510
Sabrina. Honey, come on.

01:40:25.670 --> 01:40:28.300
After all we've been through!

01:40:28.470 --> 01:40:32.310
Just do in your heart what you know
I would do if I was in your position.

01:40:35.310 --> 01:40:36.310
Okay.

01:40:41.480 --> 01:40:42.980
Sam, stop!
I don't want to hear.

01:40:43.150 --> 01:40:45.860
I'm not interested in Vargas anymore.
I'm off the story.

01:40:46.030 --> 01:40:48.200
- Peterson, too?
- No, no, no. She's still on it.

01:40:48.360 --> 01:40:49.530
You know, the girl is nuts!

01:40:49.700 --> 01:40:51.740
She went undercover
as a Chess tour guide.

01:40:51.910 --> 01:40:52.910
You're kidding!

01:40:53.080 --> 01:40:54.580
I'm serious.
She got a job there.

01:40:54.740 --> 01:40:56.660
Pete, look, look, there 's more
I wanna tell you, okay?

01:40:56.830 --> 01:40:59.120
No, Sam, don't tempt me!
I'm not gonna get killed on a story

01:40:59.290 --> 01:41:00.540
where I don't even get the girl.

01:41:00.710 --> 01:41:03.540
I'm goin' back on my book tour.
I'll be in Seattle by dinner.

01:41:03.710 --> 01:41:05.960
In a few hours, this whole thing
will be a distant memory.

01:41:06.130 --> 01:41:08.130
Okay, don't worry about it, buddy.
And good luck on the tour.

01:41:08.300 --> 01:41:10.800
Thanks for everything, man.

01:41:13.890 --> 01:41:17.140
You need to have a little chat
with your personnel director.

01:41:17.310 --> 01:41:20.230
Sabrina Peterson's
working at Chess.

01:41:20.400 --> 01:41:22.400
Oh, Jesus.

01:41:24.770 --> 01:41:27.030
He ain't gonna help us.

01:41:37.660 --> 01:41:39.750
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

01:41:42.460 --> 01:41:46.050
We hope you have enjoyed your tour, and
remember, no matter where you may live...

01:41:46.210 --> 01:41:50.300
Chess Chemical is your neighbor,
striving for a better tomorrow today.

01:41:50.470 --> 01:41:52.430
Thank you very much.

01:41:57.600 --> 01:41:59.480
Excuse me.
Does this plane have a phone?

01:41:59.640 --> 01:42:02.650
Straight ahead on the cabin wall, but you
really need to stay in your seat, sir.

01:42:02.810 --> 01:42:05.690
- We're about to take off.
- Okay, thanks.

01:42:22.710 --> 01:42:24.080
- What city, please?
- Uh, Madison.

01:42:24.250 --> 01:42:25.380
The number of the capitol building.

01:42:25.540 --> 01:42:29.170
- That's 555-4331.
- Thank you.

01:42:30.720 --> 01:42:33.430
Ladies and gentlemen,
we'll be taking off momentarily.

01:42:33.590 --> 01:42:36.800
Flight attendants,
please prepare for departure.

01:42:36.970 --> 01:42:39.310
- Good evening. State Capitol.
- Yeah, Sam Smotherman.

01:42:39.470 --> 01:42:42.480
Mr. Smotherman.
That's extension 307.

01:45:08.040 --> 01:45:11.750
Keep it movin'.
Keep comin'.

01:45:11.920 --> 01:45:15.460
Fine. Hold it right there.
Okay.

01:45:15.630 --> 01:45:18.260
- How you doin', Jack?
- Okay, Bob. How are you?

01:45:19.010 --> 01:45:21.090
Jesus! God!

01:45:21.260 --> 01:45:23.510
What are these...
Oh, Jesus!

01:45:51.670 --> 01:45:54.920
Too bad. But a definite "A"
for effort, Peterson.

01:45:55.090 --> 01:45:59.970
Or should I call you Brackett,
Mrs. Brackett? Hmm?

01:46:00.130 --> 01:46:01.880
I don't really care what
you call me, Smotherman.

01:46:02.050 --> 01:46:05.760
Or should I call you
Ernesto, Mr. Vargas?

01:46:05.930 --> 01:46:07.730
Oh, darn!

01:46:08.770 --> 01:46:10.980
I wanted to be the one
to tell you.

01:46:11.140 --> 01:46:13.230
You did!
A cop once told me...

01:46:13.400 --> 01:46:15.730
"Always look for the lie; that's when
the story begins to unravel."

01:46:15.900 --> 01:46:19.440
When I asked you what year you graduated,
you gave me two different years.

01:46:19.610 --> 01:46:22.450
I wondered why, so I looked
you up in your yearbook.

01:46:22.610 --> 01:46:27.370
Funny thing was, you weren't in it,
not under the name Smotherman, anyway.

01:46:32.460 --> 01:46:34.790
We were hoping you had what
we were looking for, but...

01:46:34.960 --> 01:46:37.130
since you don't have it,
and we don't have it...

01:46:37.300 --> 01:46:39.800
we can assume
it didn't survive the crash.

01:46:39.960 --> 01:46:44.470
So now the only evidence
to destroy is you.

01:46:44.640 --> 01:46:47.470
Oh, and your husband,
of course.

01:46:47.640 --> 01:46:51.430
Fortunately,
we know exactly where he is.

01:46:57.980 --> 01:46:59.820
- What's going on, Ted?
- Oh, Mr. Chess,

01:46:59.980 --> 01:47:01.490
I didn't know anyone was in here.

01:47:01.650 --> 01:47:03.700
We've got an alert
down at the loading dock.

01:47:03.860 --> 01:47:07.450
- Go back to your station. I'll deal with it.
- Yes, sir.

01:47:08.910 --> 01:47:11.620
Get out there.
See what's going on.

01:47:14.080 --> 01:47:16.330
How'd you get involved
in this, Sam?

01:47:16.500 --> 01:47:19.340
Willy wanted to get rid of Beekman, and
he thought you could get the job done?

01:47:19.500 --> 01:47:22.670
- Something like that.
- But you botched the fire in college.

01:47:22.840 --> 01:47:24.970
What made him think
you'd get it right this time?

01:47:25.130 --> 01:47:26.840
I was the only bad guy he knew.

01:47:29.810 --> 01:47:31.720
Did he pay you to hook up
with Senator Robbins?

01:47:31.890 --> 01:47:34.480
Think I could afford
steak dinners if he didn't'?

01:47:34.640 --> 01:47:36.560
Do me a favor, Peterson.

01:47:36.730 --> 01:47:38.530
Sit down.

01:48:00.170 --> 01:48:01.880
Stay with her, and watch her.

01:48:32.160 --> 01:48:36.160
I'm sorry to keep you waiting.
It seems...

01:48:42.250 --> 01:48:45.590
It seems we've got a traffic jam
in the parking lot.

01:48:45.760 --> 01:48:49.260
I'm in no rush. As long as
we've got a couple of minutes...

01:48:49.430 --> 01:48:51.260
What?
You want an interview?

01:48:51.430 --> 01:48:55.270
Why not? Give a dying girl
her last wish.

01:48:55.430 --> 01:49:00.400
Why'd you do it, Willy? Why not just
admit LDF was a flop and move on?

01:49:00.560 --> 01:49:04.940
For ten years, Beekman and Hervey
promised me they'd iron out the kinks.

01:49:05.110 --> 01:49:09.110
A hundred million dollars later,
they apologized, said they were wrong.

01:49:09.280 --> 01:49:12.660
By then it was too late. I mortgaged our
company's future in this thing. It had to fly!

01:49:12.830 --> 01:49:16.000
What were these kinks, exactly?

01:49:16.160 --> 01:49:19.290
Well, let's put it this way. You can't
put a label on a carton of milk:

01:49:19.460 --> 01:49:22.920
"This product has been known
to cause cancer in laboratory animals."

01:49:23.090 --> 01:49:26.630
- And Beekman was gonna blow the whistle.
- Can you imagine?

01:49:26.800 --> 01:49:31.220
The guy screws up and then he tries to bite
the hand that feeds him? Tsk, tsk, tsk, tsk.

01:49:45.150 --> 01:49:50.150
All right, that's it. I've had it.
Just get her out. Now!

01:49:50.320 --> 01:49:53.030
- Willy, let's go.
- Where's he gonna take me, Sam?

01:49:53.200 --> 01:49:56.620
- At least tell me how he's gonna do it, huh?
- No comment.

01:49:56.790 --> 01:49:58.160
Another train crash?
Another fire?

01:49:58.330 --> 01:50:00.620
Hey, maybe I'll get it the
old-fashioned way like Danny Brown.

01:50:00.790 --> 01:50:04.130
Come on, Sam, you're the organ grinder
here! Tell me how this ape's gonna do it.

01:50:05.880 --> 01:50:08.710
- Why not just show her, Mando?
- Brackett!

01:50:08.880 --> 01:50:10.590
Brackett.

01:50:12.470 --> 01:50:15.970
You got her? Just get her.
Stop shooting!

01:50:16.140 --> 01:50:19.100
Lock the gates.
Don't let anyone in.

01:50:38.120 --> 01:50:41.960
Peterson, I thought
you were one of them!

01:50:42.120 --> 01:50:46.000
It's okay.
I'm all right. I'm fine.

01:50:47.380 --> 01:50:50.510
What'd you come back for,
Brackett, me or the story?

01:50:51.840 --> 01:50:55.180
- Mostly you, Peterson.
- Mostly me?

01:50:55.970 --> 01:50:58.260
He's on the third tier!

01:52:01.580 --> 01:52:04.080
Nice try, Mando.
Drop the gun.

01:52:04.250 --> 01:52:07.580
Why? Are you going to shoot me
with your finger, Brackett?

01:52:07.750 --> 01:52:09.920
There's only one way
to find out.

01:52:51.920 --> 01:52:54.460
Any time you want to jump in,
Peterson.

01:53:14.650 --> 01:53:16.650
- Thank you!
- You're welcome.

01:53:30.830 --> 01:53:32.830
Oh, Jesus.

01:53:44.010 --> 01:53:46.010
Oh, Jesus!

01:54:05.370 --> 01:54:09.460
My mother always said, you want
the job done right, do it yourself.

01:54:12.120 --> 01:54:14.290
Whoa. Whoa.

01:54:18.380 --> 01:54:20.470
- Peterson!
- Self-defense classes.

01:54:20.630 --> 01:54:22.050
A must for a woman in the '90s.

01:54:22.220 --> 01:54:23.620
Uh-huh.

01:54:25.390 --> 01:54:28.810
- Stay there or I'll shoot.
- I don't think so.

01:54:34.980 --> 01:54:37.270
Think again.

01:55:16.100 --> 01:55:19.360
Mrs. Brackett,
you had it all the time.

01:55:26.030 --> 01:55:28.280
Uh-uh-uh.
Don't touch.

01:55:32.410 --> 01:55:35.420
Hey, Pete, do you mind
if I kill your wife?

01:55:35.580 --> 01:55:38.710
